<dl id="n04033a"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n04" href="#n04033a">N04 (VI.B.25)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n04all.htm#n04033a"> 33(a)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Vigilance Committee <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n04033a"><li>FW 34.04 </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/lexb.htm#n04033a">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/b/l39b.htm#n04033a">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n04033a">MS BL 47472-98v</ms> </li><li>JJA 45:007 <a name="b11d" href="../../ff/fdra/bda.htm#b11d">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/b/b11d.htm#n04033a">Draft: I.2&sect;1.1</a> </li> </ul><mm class="note">Note: See <a name="n03119a" href="n03all.htm#n03119a">N03 (VI.B.3):119(a)</a>. &lsquo;The Irish Vigilance Association&rsquo; was founded in 1911 under the auspices of the Dominicans. Its primary purpose was to protect Irish Catholics from the excesses of the English popular press. Volunteers were sought and a number of Vigilance Committees were set up in various parts of the country. See letter dated 11 February 1922, in <cite>James Joyce&apos;s Letters to Sylvia Beach</cite>. </mm> </dd></dl>
